'''Cheikh El Hasnaoui''' (1910–2002) was a [[Berber people|Berber]] singer born in a small town near [[Tizi Ouzou]] in [[Algeria]].  He sang Algerian [[chaabi]] music, and was, along with [[Slimane Azem]], responsible for laying the foundations of modern popular [[Kabyle language|Kabyle]] music in the 1950s and 1960s.<ref>

Korpe, Marie (2004) ''Shoot the singer!: music censorship today''. Zed Books. {{ISBN|1-84277-505-7}} [https://books.google.com/books?id=-Yc0xnSfS8EC&lpg=PA116&dq=cheikh%20el%20hasnaoui&pg=PA116#v=onepage&q=cheikh%20el%20hasnaoui&f=false p.116.]</ref>

He died in 2002 at [[Saint-Pierre, Réunion|Saint Pierre de la Reunion]], [[France]].

