{{Orphan|date=February 2013}}

'''Ngātata-i-te-rangi ''' (? &ndash; 1854) was a [[New Zealand]] [[Te Āti Awa]] leader, and belonged to the Ngāi Te Whiti [[hapū]].<ref name="DNZB ">{{DNZB|title=Ngatata-i-te-rangi |first= Angela|last= Ballara|id=1n11  |accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref>

Ngātata-i-te-rangi was the son of Te Rangiwhetiki and brother of Te Marokura. He married Whetowheto and had five children, one being [[Wi Tako Ngātata]]. Later in life he had a second wife and they had a daughter named Meri Haratua.<ref name="NZHistory_Ngatata-i-te-rangi">{{cite web|title=Ngatata-i-te-rangi|url=http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/politics/treaty/signatory/8-10|publisher=Research and Publishing Group of the New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage|accessdate=29 April 2016}}</ref>

Ngātata-i-te-rangi established Kumutoto [[Pā]] alongside [[Wiremu Piti Pomare|Wi Piti Pomare]].

Ngātata-i-te-rangi signed the [[Treaty of Waitangi]] in Wellington on 29 April 1840.

