{{Infobox Officeholder | honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]] | name = Viola Léger | honorific-suffix = | image = | imagesize = | office = [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] for L'Acadie, New Brunswick | appointed = [[Jean Chrétien]] | term_start = June 13, 2001 | term_end = June 29, 2005 | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1930|06|29}} | birth_place = [[Fitchburg, Massachusetts]], U.S. | death_date = | death_place = | party = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] | alma_mater = [[Boston University]] }}
'''Viola Léger''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|OC|ONB}} (born June 29, 1930) is an [[United States|American]]-[[Canada|Canadian]] actress and former [[Senate of Canada|Canadian Senator]].
Born in [[Fitchburg, Massachusetts]], Léger received a B.A. and a B.Ed. from the [[Université de Moncton]], and an M.F.A. (Theater Education) from [[Boston University]].{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} She was appointed to the Senate at the recommendation of [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] [[Jean Chrétien]], in 2001, representing the Senatorial division of L'Acadie, New Brunswick. She was a member of the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] caucus. Léger retired from the Senate when she reached the age of 75.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}
In 1989, she was made an Officer of the [[Order of Canada]]. In 2007, she was awarded the [[Order of New Brunswick]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gnb.ca/cnb/news/iga/2007e1002ig.htm|title=Order of New Brunswick recipients announced}}</ref> Ms. Léger received a [[Governor General's Performing Arts Award]] in 2013 for her work as an actress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ggpaa.ca/recipients|title=Award Recipients}}</ref>
